{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17608460","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17608460"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T13:32:47+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T13:32:47+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16000"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16000","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16000"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0.22,0.04,0.7,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8691"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66581"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8691","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8691"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16000"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52034"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4693"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4949"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"7567"},{"type":"tags","id":"8130"},{"type":"tags","id":"9616"},{"type":"tags","id":"9621"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"20798"},{"type":"contributions","id":"20800"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22279"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66581","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/66581"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA newborn presents with protrusion of intestinal contents through the anterior abdominal wall. The defect is located just lateral to an intact umbilical cord, and the exposed bowel has no protective membrane covering it.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely congenital anomaly?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Umbilical hernia","Omphalocele","Pentalogy of Cantrell","Gastroschisis","Limb-body wall complex"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis description is characteristic of \u003Cstrong\u003Egastroschisis\u003C/strong\u003E, which presents as a full-thickness paraumbilical defect with herniation of bowel without a covering sac. The defect typically occurs to the right of an intact umbilical cord.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUmbilical hernia\u003C/strong\u003E involves protrusion through the umbilical ring with intact skin coverage\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOmphalocele\u003C/strong\u003E occurs through the umbilical ring and always has a protective membranous sac covering the herniated contents\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPentalogy of Cantrell\u003C/strong\u003E involves multiple midline defects including sternal, diaphragmatic, pericardial, cardiac and abdominal wall abnormalities\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELimb-body wall complex\u003C/strong\u003E is characterised by multiple severe defects including limb abnormalities and complex body wall defects\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EGastroschisis requires urgent surgical management to prevent fluid losses and bowel injury. Unlike an omphalocele, a gastroschisis is rarely associated with other congenital anomalies.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Gastroschisis is a paraumbilical defect with herniation of bowel without a covering sac","Gastroschisis occurs lateral to an intact umbilical cord, while omphalocele occurs through the umbilical ring with a membranous sac","Anterior abdominal wall defects are important to distinguish as their management and associated anomalies differ"],"references":["Wojcik MH, Agrawal PB. Deciphering congenital anomalies for the next generation. Cold Spring Harb Mol Case Stud. 2020 Oct 7;6(5):a005504. doi: 10.1101/mcs.a005504. PMID: 32826208; PMCID: PMC7552931.","Bhat V, Moront M, Bhandari V. Gastroschisis: A State-of-the-Art Review. Children (Basel). 2020 Dec 17;7(12):302. doi: 10.3390/children7120302. PMID: 33348575; PMCID: PMC7765881.","Arulkumaran, S., Ledger, W., Denny, L., \u0026 Doumouchtsis, S. (Eds.). (2019). Oxford Textbook of Obstetrics and Gynaecology. Oxford University Press.","Singh, V. (2022). Textbook of clinical embryology, -E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52034"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16000"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52034","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/52034"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-01T09:12:49+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-01T09:13:15+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8691"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66581"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"